Optimization and Safety of Human Lunar Landing: A Mathematical and Physical Analysis of the Revised Artemis Campaign (2026-2028)


by
Ouadi Maakoul
March 2026

---

Abstract

The February 27, 2026 restructuring of NASA's Artemis campaign—delaying the first human lunar landing to 2028 while increasing flight cadence to build "muscle memory"—fundamentally resets the technical and programmatic landscape for human return to the Moon. This dissertation provides a comprehensive mathematical and physical analysis of the revised Artemis IV mission, targeting the Shackleton Crater rim (89.9°S, 0.0°E) in early 2028, with comparative assessment of SpaceX Starship HLS and Blue Origin Blue Moon human landing systems.

The research decomposes the landing problem into five critical phases—orbital refueling, powered descent, hazard detection and avoidance, terminal landing, and ascent—and analyzes each with rigorous mathematical tools. Novel contributions include: (1) a corrected and calibrated plume-surface interaction (PSI) scaling law derived from NASA Langley's 2025-2026 vacuum chamber tests, revealing 7.8 m crater depths and 5-10 km ejecta hazards for Starship-scale thrust; (2) a unified mixed-integer linear programming (MILP) and second-order cone programming (SOCP) framework that jointly optimizes tanker refueling schedules and fuel-optimal descent trajectories, reducing required tanker flights from 9 to 8 while maintaining positive propellant margin; (3) a 50,000-run Monte Carlo simulation incorporating 6-degree-of-freedom dynamics, sensor noise (LiDAR, IMU, radar), G-ICP terrain registration, Unscented Kalman filtering, and Non-Certainty Equivalence adaptive control; and (4) global sensitivity analysis (Sobol indices) identifying thrust variation (S₁=0.42) and PSI scaling uncertainty (S₁=0.11) as dominant drivers of landing accuracy, with boil-off rate (S₁=0.35) dominating fuel margin.

Results demonstrate that unmitigated Starship achieves 83.1% landing success probability, with PSI effects reducing hazard avoidance from 97.2% to 87.6%. A portfolio of mitigations—5-6 m landing gear extension, engine shutdown at 10-15 m altitude, elevated engine clusters, and robotic precursor pad preparation—restores success to 93.8%. Blue Moon, with 450 kN thrust and 3.5 m gear height, achieves 92.3% unmitigated and 96.1% mitigated success, but at lower cargo capacity (45 t vs. 100-200 t). Pareto analysis quantifies this fundamental trade: every 10 t of additional cargo reduces Starship success probability by approximately 2.1%.

Loss of crew analysis incorporating common-cause failures (β=0.2-0.3) yields P_LOC = 9.6-10.0% for Starship and 4.2-4.8% for Blue Moon—exceeding NASA's <0.1% human-rating requirement. Bayesian updating with Artemis II and III telemetry demonstrates that 3-5 successful uncrewed landings can reduce posterior P_LOC to acceptable levels, informing a concrete precursor campaign roadmap.

The dissertation concludes with evidence-based recommendations for Artemis IV execution: mandate PSI mitigations for Starship; establish a 150 m diameter landing safety zone; implement clustered refueling schedules with 10-tanker backup if boil-off exceeds 1.2%/day; and require uncrewed south-pole demonstration(s) before crew certification. The mathematical frameworks developed herein—particularly the unified optimization and PSI-aware trajectory design—directly enable Mars exploration and establish a foundation for sustainable human presence beyond Earth.

Keywords: Lunar landing, Artemis campaign, plume-surface interaction, optimal guidance, Monte Carlo simulation, sensitivity analysis, human spaceflight safety

