4.9 Summary

This chapter has developed the mathematical framework for navigation and control of a lunar lander, with specific application to the Artemis IV mission:

1. Sensor suite: LiDAR (primary), radar altimeter, stereo cameras, and tactical-grade IMU provide redundant measurements for all phases.
2. MoonFALL: Provides 2 cm ground sampling at 500 m altitude, enabling precise hazard detection and terrain-relative navigation.
3. G-ICP registration: Probabilistic point cloud matching that incorporates measurement uncertainty and surface structure, achieving 0.05-0.25 m registration accuracy.
4. UKF estimation: Fuses IMU propagation with intermittent updates, handling nonlinear dynamics and quaternion constraints. Expected position errors < 0.5 m at touchdown.
5. NCE adaptive control: Uses parameter uncertainty to improve transient response, with Lyapunov-stable adaptation and sliding mode robustness.
6. Fault detection: Continuous monitoring of sensor and actuator health with graceful degradation strategies.

The navigation and control architecture developed here provides the foundation for the Monte Carlo simulations in Chapter 6. The sensor error models ($\sigma_r$, $\sigma_\theta$, $\sigma_R$, etc.) and control gains ($\mathbf{K}_D$, $\Gamma$, $\lambda$) defined in this chapter will be used as inputs to the 50,000-run simulation. The expected navigation accuracy (Section 4.6.1) will be compared against the actual landing ellipse results (Section 6.3) to validate the filter design.

With the physical constraints (Chapter 2), propulsion system (Chapter 3), and navigation/control framework (Chapter 4) established, we now turn to mission architecture—how these elements are integrated into a coherent campaign to land humans on the Moon in early 2028.